25|$|Several left-wing or socialist groupings have an overt {{environmental}} concern, whereas several green parties {{contain a}} strong socialist presence. For example, the Green Party of England and Wales features an eco-socialist group, Green Left, that {{was founded in}} June 2005 and whose members held a number of influential positions within the party, including both the former Principal Speakers Siân Berry and Dr. Derek Wall, himself an eco-socialist and Marxist academic. In Europe, some Green left political parties combine traditional social-democratic values such as a desire for greater economic equality and <b>workers</b> <b>rights</b> with demands for environmental protection, such as the Nordic Green Left.|$|E
