25|$|Those {{focused on}} working {{conditions}} included Friedrich Engels, whose book The Condition of the Working Class in England in 1844 would inspire the Marxist movement named for his collaborator, Karl Marx. In the United Kingdom the Factory Act was revised six further times between 1844 and 1878 {{to help improve}} the condition of workers by limiting work hours {{and the use of}} child labor. The formation of the International Labour Organization in 1919 under the League of Nations and then the United Nations sought to address the plight of workers the world over. Concern over working conditions as described by muckraker journalists during the Progressive Era in the United States saw the passage of new <b>workers</b> <b>rights</b> laws and ultimately resulted in the Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938, passed during the New Deal.|$|E
